  <h2>Alberta Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Alberta is a classic short-season prairie climate: rapid spring transition, strong mid-summer heat,
    then a fast slide toward cooler nights by late August. Success here usually comes down to whether
    your crop’s maturity requirement realistically fits the heat you have left — not just the calendar date.
  </p>

  <h3>1) The season builds fast — and shuts down fast</h3>
  <p>
    June and July can accumulate heat quickly, especially across central and southern Alberta.
    But late-season cooling often arrives abruptly. Once nights begin trending toward single digits (°C),
    warm-season crops slow dramatically.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    By early August in many areas, new long-season warm crops become increasingly risky without protection.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Maturity rating matters more than planting date</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Choose shorter-season varieties.</strong> A 55-day sweet corn often succeeds where a 75-day fails.</li>
    <li><strong>Shave maturity where possible.</strong> When remaining GDD is tight, reducing days-to-maturity by 10–20% improves odds.</li>
    <li><strong>Be realistic late in the season.</strong> Full-season winter squash or long peppers rarely finish if started too late.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3) Regional differences within Alberta</h3>
  <p>
    Alberta is not uniform. Your effective growing window depends heavily on location:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Southern Alberta:</strong> Longer heat accumulation, but wind exposure and dry conditions are common.</li>
    <li><strong>Central Alberta:</strong> Moderate heat build with noticeable late-summer cooldown.</li>
    <li><strong>Northern Alberta:</strong> Long daylight hours help growth, but frost risk can arrive earlier.</li>
    <li><strong>Foothills & higher elevations:</strong> Shorter seasons and greater frost-pocket risk.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="small muted">
    Even small elevation changes or sheltered vs. exposed sites can shift frost timing by weeks.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Transplants and protection extend your margin</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use transplants for warm-season crops.</strong> Starting ahead indoors often makes the difference.</li>
    <li><strong>Plan for row cover or low tunnels.</strong> A few protected nights can carry crops across the finish line.</li>
    <li><strong>Watch overnight lows, not just daytime highs.</strong> Cool nights slow maturity significantly.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Start with the frost and remaining GDD tables above.</li>
    <li>Compare crop maturity requirements to remaining seasonal heat.</li>
    <li>Add a safety buffer if you’re in a frost pocket or higher elevation.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    Use the tables above as your baseline, then sanity-check a specific crop + planting date in the
    <a href="/tools/gdd-planner/">GDD Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>